        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Riverside, CA: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Riverside, CA, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Riverside Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Riverside Fire Extinguisher Inspection Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Riverside enforces the California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Four inspection intervals apply to every commercial extinguisher.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Riverside is the Inland Empire's largest city and the seat of Riverside County. The commercial landscape spans the historic Downtown Mission Inn corridor, the University Avenue commercial district, Tyler Mall area retail, and significant industrial and warehouse facilities along the I-215 and SR-60 corridors. Riverside's proximity to wildland-urban interface areas makes fire safety compliance a heightened priority for the Riverside Fire Department.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by your own trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, the tamper seal is intact, and the pull pin is in place. Document every monthly check. In the event of a fire incident or an enforcement action, the absence of monthly records significantly increases your liability exposure.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed fire protection technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle integrity, and overall unit condition — then attaches a dated service tag. California requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold an OSFM license. All annual inspections, 6-year internals, and 12-year hydrostatic tests must be performed by OSFM-licensed technicians. Verify licensing at osfm.fire.ca.gov. Any unit that fails must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation that external inspections miss. This typically includes a complete recharge. Missing the 6-year exam is a frequently cited violation during Riverside Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must undergo hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned. After passing, units are recharged and marked with the new test date. Plan for some units to require replacement at the 12-year mark — budget accordingly.</p>

